WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
backing up sensitive data, processing certain sensitive data, all sorts of things like this.

00:05.000 --> 00:10.000
And so let's briefly talk about this concept of having a risk management.

00:22.000 --> 00:25.000
We've talked through a ton of concepts now related to risk management.

00:25.000 --> 00:30.000
How organizations have to identify their most valuable assets, identify all the risks associated with them.

00:42.000 --> 00:45.000
We've talked through a ton of concepts now related to risk management.

00:45.000 --> 00:52.000
How organizations have to identify their most valuable assets, identify all the risks associated with those assets, treat all those risks.

00:52.000 --> 00:57.000
We've talked about all of this from the perspective of companies looking at their own systems and assets.

00:57.000 --> 01:03.000
But what's incredibly common nowadays is that organizations outsource a ton of stuff.

01:03.000 --> 01:10.000
They have a ton of different service providers that provide all sorts of often very sensitive and confidential services for an organization,

01:10.000 --> 01:15.000
backing up sensitive data, processing certain sensitive data, all sorts of things like this.

01:15.000 --> 01:21.000
And so let's briefly talk about this concept of having a risk management supply chain.

01:21.000 --> 01:28.000
And what that simply means is that an organization needs to understand all the services that they have from different service providers,

01:28.000 --> 01:35.000
and then conduct all of this risk management process that we've just talked about on their service providers.

01:35.000 --> 01:41.000
So understanding what data is being outsourced, what processes are being outsourced, and what are the risks associated with that.

01:41.000 --> 01:48.000
Now it's very common for instance that data is outsourced, and data is an extremely valuable asset to an organization.

01:48.000 --> 01:55.000
So an organization needs to understand what assets being outsourced, what are the risks associated with that service provider,

01:55.000 --> 01:58.000
and then how are they going to treat those risks.

01:58.000 --> 02:04.000
And this is one of the big challenges with outsourcing is that when an organization outsources something to a service provider,

02:04.000 --> 02:09.000
they now have far less direct control over the protection mechanisms that they can put in place,

02:09.000 --> 02:14.000
they can put in place to protect that valuable asset, the data.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000
And really what organizations can typically rely on is not putting in place their own controls,

02:19.000 --> 02:24.000
but rather requesting that the service provider put in place certain controls.

02:24.000 --> 02:29.000
And so a big part of risk management supply chain is identifying the risks,

02:29.000 --> 02:36.000
and then making sure that the contracts, the SLAs, the PLAs, whatever contracting vehicle the organization is using.

02:36.000 --> 02:47.000
Make sure that it's explicitly stated in that contract, what controls the service provider needs to put in place to mitigate the risks that the organization is concerned with.

02:47.000 --> 02:50.000
So that's the concept of a risk management supply chain.

02:50.000 --> 02:55.000
One final piece we'll talk about in this risk management domain, and that is risk frameworks.

02:55.000 --> 03:02.000
We'll talk about frameworks in more detail in domain 3, but for now frameworks are something that provide comprehensive guidance.

03:03.000 --> 03:09.000
They allow organizations to have a roadmap, have a set of guidance that says, you know, for instance,

03:09.000 --> 03:14.000
this director relates to risk management, if you want to put in place a risk management function,

03:14.000 --> 03:19.000
are you just going to start with a blank piece of paper and try and make it up and hope it works well?

03:19.000 --> 03:22.000
Well, you're going to go to a well established framework that says,

03:22.000 --> 03:25.000
here's exactly how you put in place a risk management process.

03:25.000 --> 03:27.000
Here's the different controls that should be in place.

03:27.000 --> 03:29.000
Here's who should be accountable, responsible for what?

03:29.000 --> 03:30.000
Here's how it should work.

03:30.000 --> 03:36.000
So there is guidance out there that can help us figure all this out to not only build a new process,

03:36.000 --> 03:41.000
but also to look at our existing process and say, how well does this align to industry best practices?

03:41.000 --> 03:44.000
And you don't have to be an expert on any of the four frameworks we have listed here,

03:44.000 --> 03:49.000
but just be aware that these frameworks exist and be aware of what you can use them for,

03:49.000 --> 03:53.000
which is to help you build a new process or to evaluate an existing process.

03:53.000 --> 03:59.000
And so NIST 800-37, ISO 31,000, COSO, COVID Risk IT,

03:59.000 --> 04:02.000
these are just examples of risk frameworks.

04:02.000 --> 04:04.000
And now you know we can use them for.

